<methodology slug="pm-tool-selection">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Evaluation framework for selecting a PM tool: MoSCoW requirements, weighted scoring, POC testing, TCO analysis, and decision documentation with mandatory human sign-off at three gates.</summary>
    <category>tool-selection</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>pm-tools</tag>
      <tag>evaluation</tag>
      <tag>procurement</tag>
      <tag>tco</tag>
      <tag>decision-making</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>PM Tool Selection Framework</title>

    <summary>Structured evaluation framework for selecting or replacing a project management tool. Gather requirements via MoSCoW matrix, run a time-boxed 2-week POC on real project data, score tools against weighted criteria, compute 3-year TCO, and document the decision as an ADR. Human sign-off is mandatory at requirements, POC scoring, and final decision — agents must not pick the tool unilaterally.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>PM tool switches fail when driven by single-person preference or novelty bias rather than documented requirements and evidence. Weighted scorecards with explicit criteria prevent rationalization theater; TCO models surface migration and training costs that per-seat pricing hides; and ADR documentation gives future teams the context to revisit without starting over.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>New team picking a first PM tool, or current tool causing documented friction</item>
        <item>Vendor renewal cycle where a price jump triggers re-evaluation</item>
        <item>Post-acquisition consolidation across two tool stacks</item>
        <item>Compliance shift (SOC2, HIPAA, EU data residency) forcing reassessment</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Teams under 5 people with simple workflow — pick GitHub Projects or Linear free tier, skip the matrix</item>
        <item>Mid-project under deadline pressure — switching tools mid-flight burns more than it saves</item>
        <item>Single-issue gripe (e.g., "velocity report is ugly") — fix the report, do not migrate</item>
        <item>Decision already made by leadership — running a theater POC erodes trust</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="requirements-gathering">
      <p>Involve all roles in requirements gathering — PM, developer, admin, and PMO — not just power users. Admins see the migration cost that power users ignore.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Involve all roles in requirements gathering — PM, developer, admin, and PMO — not just power users; admins see the migration cost that power users ignore.</statement>
        <rationale>POC participants self-select toward novelty; admin and PMO interviews surface long-tail integration and governance requirements that only appear after 3-6 months of production use.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Classify requirements as Must/Should/Nice (MoSCoW); designate at least one criterion as a deal-breaker (e.g., "no SAML = eliminated") to break tied scores.</statement>
        <rationale>Weighted scorecards without deal-breakers produce close scores that rationalize any pre-made decision; a deal-breaker forces early elimination and honest evaluation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="templates/requirements.yaml">MoSCoW requirements matrix with must/should/nice/constraints</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="weighted-scoring-framework">
      <p>Score tools across five weighted categories: Core Features (30%), Usability (25%), Integrations (20%), Enterprise (15%), Cost (10%). Source each score from direct testing or cited documentation — not vendor claims alone.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Score before the POC, then re-score after — variance reveals which criteria were assumed wrong.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-POC scores surface assumption gaps; post-POC scores are grounded in real use. A large variance flags criteria that were guessed rather than known.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run the POC on a real epic with 8-15 issues from actual project data — not toy tickets; toy data flatters every tool.</statement>
        <rationale>Vendor sales engineers tune POC environments to show strengths; only real data reveals workflow friction, performance under load, and integration gaps.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="tco-calculation">
      <p>Compute 3-year TCO including direct (license), indirect (implementation, migration, training, admin), and hidden costs (productivity loss, integration development).</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Compute 3-year TCO including direct (license), indirect (implementation, migration, training, admin), and hidden costs (productivity loss, integration development).</statement>
        <rationale>Per-seat pricing typically represents 20-40% of year-1 TCO; migration and retraining costs dominate the first year and are systematically underestimated.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="templates/tco.yaml">3-year TCO model with all cost categories</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="decision-and-exit-testing">
      <p>Test the data export on day 3 of the POC and document the decision as an Architecture Decision Record (ADR).</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Test the data export on day 3 of the POC — run a full data export and inspect the dump for completeness and portability.</statement>
        <rationale>Vendor lock-in risk is only visible when you attempt to leave; discovering export limitations before commitment avoids a multi-year hostage situation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Running a POC on a decision already made by leadership.</description>
        <reason>Theater POCs erode trust when the team recognizes the outcome is predetermined; skip the process or run a genuine evaluation.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Switching tools mid-project under deadline pressure.</description>
        <reason>Tool migration cost — lost automations, broken integrations, retrained muscle memory — always exceeds the friction being escaped during an active project.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <reference path="templates/adr.md">ADR template for documenting the final tool decision</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="engineering-focused-tools">
      <p>Quick-reference profiles for engineering-focused project management tools.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Jira Cloud — Best for enterprise + compliance (50+ users, $8-16/user). Strengths: customizable, large ecosystem, JQL power. Weaknesses: complex UI, historically slow performance, expensive at scale.</item>
        <item>Linear — Best for engineering teams (10-100 users, $8-16/user). Strengths: keyboard-first speed, opinionated UX, strong GitHub integration. Weaknesses: less flexible than Jira, smaller ecosystem, newer vendor.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects v2 — Best for OSS and developer-native teams (any size, $0-21/user). Strengths: integrated with code, GraphQL API, no context-switch. Weaknesses: limited PM features, no time tracking, GraphQL-only.</item>
        <item>GitLab — Best for DevOps teams wanting one platform (10-1000 users, $0-99/user). Strengths: full DevOps loop, self-host option, REST + GraphQL. Weaknesses: complex pricing, Premium-gated WIP/iterations.</item>
        <item>Azure DevOps — Best for Microsoft shops with compliance requirements (50+, $6-52/user). Strengths: enterprise-grade, Azure AD auth, Boards + Pipelines + Plans. Weaknesses: Microsoft-centric, complex onboarding.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="all-in-one-and-non-technical-tools">
      <p>Quick-reference profiles for all-in-one and non-technical project management tools.</p>

      <list>
        <item>ClickUp — Best for all-in-one needs (10-500 users, $7-19/user). Strengths: feature-rich, highly customizable, docs integration. Weaknesses: can be overwhelming, performance concerns at scale, complex permissions.</item>
        <item>Notion — Best for docs + PM combo (5-100, $8-18/user). Strengths: flexible, excellent documentation, AI features. Weaknesses: not PM-focused, API does not expose all UI features, formulas limited.</item>
        <item>Asana — Best for marketing and ops teams (10-500, $11-25/user). Strengths: clean UX, goal tracking, portfolio views. Weaknesses: less dev-focused, expensive at enterprise scale.</item>
        <item>Monday.com — Best for non-technical teams (10-500, $8-20/user). Strengths: visual, flexible, no-code automations. Weaknesses: expensive at scale, PM-lite compared to Jira.</item>
        <item>Trello — Best for simple kanban teams (5-50, $0-17.50/user). Strengths: easy to use, fast onboarding, Power-Ups. Weaknesses: limited scaling, no sprint or EVM features.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="open-source-self-hosted-alternatives">
      <p>Open-source self-hosted project management alternatives.</p>

      <list>
        <item>OpenProject — Gantt + WBS native, REST API, self-hostable (https://www.openproject.org)</item>
        <item>Plane — Linear alternative, self-hostable, Python API (https://plane.so)</item>
        <item>Taiga — Scrum/Kanban, REST API, Python backend (https://taiga.io)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-friendliness-notes">
      <p>PM tool API design considerations for agentic workflows.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Jira Cloud: REST v3 + JQL, mature, rate-limited per tenant — best for complex automations.</item>
        <item>Linear: GraphQL API, webhooks, fast, opinionated schema — best for engineering-heavy agentic workflows.</item>
        <item>ClickUp: REST API exists but quirky pagination and fragile custom field handling — test before committing.</item>
        <item>Notion: API does not expose timeline, formulas, or all UI features — validate agent use case against API docs first.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects v2: GraphQL only, no REST; requires explicit schema understanding for agent use.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-evaluation-workflow">
      <p>Automation and subagent orchestration for tool evaluation.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Human sign-off is mandatory at three points: requirements sign-off, POC scoring, and final ADR approval — agents must not select the tool unilaterally.</statement>
        <rationale>A multi-year tool commitment is irreversible on the scale of a sprint; decision authority for irreversible choices belongs to humans with full organizational context.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>A requirements-gatherer agent runs async interviews, normalizes responses into a MoSCoW matrix, and a vendor-researcher agent pulls live pricing and feature data. A TCO modeler builds the 3-year model. A human reviews all three before the POC begins.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <p>Specialized subagent archetypes for evaluation automation.</p>

      <list>
        <item>requirements-gatherer — runs structured interview templates (current_state, workflow_needs, team_context, future_needs), extracts must/should/nice into YAML.</item>
        <item>vendor-researcher — pulls feature matrices, pricing, SOC2/GDPR posture from vendor docs + G2/Capterra; cites source URL per field; flags data older than 90 days.</item>
        <item>tco-modeler — builds 3-year TCO with license, implementation, training, admin, and hidden costs.</item>
        <item>adr-drafter — produces ADR-style decision record with evaluation summary and migration plan.</item>
      </list>

      <reference path="templates/fetch-pricing.sh">Script to snapshot vendor pricing pages for diff-review</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="vendor-research-prompt-pattern">
      <p>Prompt template for reliable vendor data extraction.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Vendor research with citation enforcement">
        <note>Forces citation per field; fails if data is stale or vendor-supplied without verification:</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are a vendor-researcher subagent. For each tool in {tools}, fetch:
- Current pricing tiers (per-user, per-month, annual discount)
- SSO/SAML availability per tier
- Native integrations with {required_integrations}
- API rate limits and auth model
Return JSON conforming to schema {pm_tool_profile.json}. Cite source URL per field.
Flag any score where source data is older than 90 days or marked "vendor-supplied".
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Common failure modes when automating tool evaluation.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM confidently asserts vendor features without a citation URL.</description>
        <reason>LLMs hallucinate vendor features; pricing pages change quarterly without announcement. Gate every feature claim on a live-fetched citation; fail closed if no URL is provided.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent scores mobile app quality at 8/10 without testing the app on a physical device.</description>
        <reason>Synthetic mobile UX scores are fiction; outsource physical-device testing to a human evaluator or defer the criterion.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>ADR-drafting agent consistently favours Linear over alternatives.</description>
        <reason>Training data bias from developer Twitter skews toward Linear; force the agent to argue the strongest case for the second-place tool before writing the final recommendation.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <list>
        <item>Pricing pages change quietly; cache + diff weekly — do not trust last month's research in scoring.</item>
        <item>POC scorecard suffers from the agent flattering the user's apparent preference; randomize tool order in prompts.</item>
        <item>Never commit to a multi-year contract from agent output alone; require human sign-off on any annual subscription commitment.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <p>Command-line tools and API access for PM platforms.</p>

      <p>CLI tools:</p>
      <list>
        <item>jira (Atlassian CLI) — Query Jira via JQL, export issues (https://github.com/ankitpokhrel/jira-cli)</item>
        <item>linear-cli — Linear issue CRUD, workflow inspect (npm i -g @linear/cli)</item>
        <item>gh — GitHub Projects v2 via GraphQL (https://cli.github.com)</item>
        <item>glab — GitLab issues, boards, milestones (https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/cli)</item>
        <item>clickup-cli (community) — ClickUp tasks, lists, spaces (npm packages, varies by maintainer)</item>
        <item>notion-cli (unofficial) — Notion DB query/update (Multiple Go/Python wrappers)</item>
      </list>

      <p>Services &amp; apps:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Jira Cloud (SaaS) — Yes to agents — REST v3 + JQL, mature, rate-limited per tenant</item>
        <item>Linear (SaaS) — Yes to agents — GraphQL API, webhooks, fast, opinionated schema</item>
        <item>ClickUp (SaaS) — Partial to agents — REST API exists but quirky pagination, custom fields fragile</item>
        <item>Notion (SaaS) — Partial to agents — API does not expose all UI features (timeline, formulas limited)</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects v2 (SaaS) — Yes to agents — GraphQL only, no REST; tightly coupled to issues/PRs</item>
        <item>GitLab (SaaS/OSS) — Yes to agents — REST + GraphQL, self-host option, full DevOps loop</item>
        <item>Azure DevOps (SaaS) — Yes to agents — REST API, Azure AD auth, enterprise-strong</item>
        <item>OpenProject (OSS) — Yes to agents — Self-hostable, REST API, Gantt + WBS native</item>
        <item>Plane (OSS) — Yes to agents — Self-hostable Linear alternative, Python API</item>
        <item>Taiga (OSS) — Yes to agents — Scrum/Kanban, REST API, Python backend</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Proven patterns for tool evaluation and procurement.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Score before POC, then re-score after — variance reveals which criteria were assumed wrong.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-POC scores surface assumption gaps; post-POC scores are grounded in real use. A large variance flags criteria that were guessed rather than known.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run POC on a real epic with 8-15 issues, not toy tickets — toy data flatters every tool.</statement>
        <rationale>Vendor sales engineers tune the POC environment; production behavior diverges. Real data reveals workflow friction, performance, and integration gaps.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Force one criterion to "deal-breaker" status (e.g., "no SAML = out") to break tied scores.</statement>
        <rationale>Tied scores encourage rationalization; a deal-breaker forces early elimination and binary clarity.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Interview the admin/PMO, not just power users — admins see the migration cost.</statement>
        <rationale>Power users focus on feature breadth; admins see integrations, permissions, governance, and the switching overhead that determines real success.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Ask vendors for their churn-back rate (customers who came from a competitor) — Linear and ClickUp will share, Jira will not.</statement>
        <rationale>Churn-back rate measures the tool's ability to retain customers who evaluated alternatives; it is a stronger signal than aggregate ratings which mix use-case-mismatches with genuine quality issues.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Test exit: run a full data export on day 3 of the POC and inspect the dump.</statement>
        <rationale>Vendor lock-in risk is only visible when you attempt to leave; discovering export limitations before commitment avoids a multi-year hostage situation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pricing: always negotiate annual + multi-year, ask for "engineering discount" or "open-source-friendly" rate.</statement>
        <rationale>PM tool vendors routinely discount 20-40% on multi-year commitments negotiated before renewal; the list price is a ceiling, not a floor.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="where-it-fails">
      <p>Known limitations and failure modes of the evaluation framework.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Weighted scorecards become rationalization theater when leadership has pre-decided</item>
        <item>POC participants self-select toward novelty (Linear) over depth (Jira), skewing scores</item>
        <item>TCO models miss switching cost: lost automations, broken integrations, retrained reflexes</item>
        <item>Vendor sales engineers tune the POC environment; production behavior diverges</item>
        <item>Long-tail integrations (custom Jira plugins, Asana reporting) only surface 3-6 months in</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/requirements.yaml" purpose="MoSCoW requirements matrix with must/should/nice/constraints sections"/>
      <template path="templates/tco.yaml" purpose="3-year TCO model: direct, indirect, hidden costs"/>
      <template path="templates/adr.md" purpose="ADR template for documenting the tool decision with evaluation summary"/>
      <template path="templates/fetch-pricing.sh" purpose="Snapshot vendor pricing pages for diff-review"/>
    </templates>

